This ain’t gonna kill me. 🥷🏾😤

The words I told myself every day of 2020.

2020 was one of the toughest years of my life. Newly wed, unemployed, and recovering from double inguinal hernia surgery mid-pandemic. 

Some of my lowest points were reached that year. Mental and physical pain. I chose not to accept depression. Not to accept weakness. I learned to draw power from that pain and find comedy in feeling sorry for myself. I channeled all my failures, burned them, and built a new man from the ashes. 🔥 Physical fitness was the foundation of my redemption. This is a reminder to myself and to you…to remember to always return to that foundation when in doubt. 🏃🏾🏋🏽‍♂️💪🏽

#physicalfitness #physicaltherapy #healing #recovery #mentalhealthawareness #strength #perserverance #lightattheendofthetunnel

For years I heard people talk about Joshua Tree, CA…but I couldn’t understand the allure. 

A desert wasteland with rocks…. BiG DeAL….well…somehow that desert wasteland with rocks is one of the most beautiful sights I’ve ever seen. 

The gravity of “creation”, erosion, relentless plant life, and battle hardened desert creatures weighs on my mind. Since visiting a few weeks ago, I’ve been daydreaming about the vast expanse of boulders that appear to have been PLACED carefully by giants. Trying to wrap my head around seeing trees growing atop cliff edges and rocks as large as apartment buildings. I don’t really have the right words to describe this place. 

Also…it was the perfect time of year to visit. And the perfect group of people to spend the time with. ☀️🙏🏽

I always noticed my older Asian neighbors taking time alone to move every day. Always solo…and generally early in morning. The movements appeared random to me…and “unproductive”…

but regardless of what I thought…these folks always stayed MOBILE in their old age. 🕺🏻

I watched my OWN grandparents lose their mobility as they grew old. I also NEVER saw them exercise or move in any way other than cooking, gardening, or sewing while they were alive. 😞 I hope to help my own parents stay mobile in their middle age, but I need to practice what I preach. 

I’ve started to incorporate some “random” mobility movements on my rest days respective to the muscle group I worked the day prior. Just doing the same things I saw my old neighbors do. Well…you probably haven’t read this far…but if you have, you have great control over your impulse to doom scroll. Nicely done. Anyways, I’m just spending a few quality minutes alone in the sunlight. ☀️ You should do the same when you can.

Atmosphere credit to my in-laws. 🏝️

Just returned from a 3-Day Wilderness Safety & Survival Course by @survival_expert in Big Bear. What an epic weekend. 😮‍💨🤘

We were tested physically, mentally, and intellectually…and I certainly left stronger than when I arrived. 

I’ve studied and practiced survival skills for years, but this was my FIRST wilderness survival experience in the snow + freezing temps. 🥶

I feel so much more confident in my abilities this week. Not only do I feel like a more competent outdoorsman and survivalist…but I feel like a more competent human being; better equipped to handle outdoor emergency situations or care for others who need help. 

Tested my limits, met great people, and spent time in my favorite biome. 🏔️

Remember, the best time to practice your survival skills is BEFORE you find yourself in a survival situation, not when your back’s against the wall. 

Check out @survival_expert if you’re interested in learning more about their course offerings in Nor Cal and So Cal. 🤙 Thomas Coyne earned my respect years ago, and his camp continues to make me a better, stronger adventurer. Special thanks to Adam, our instructor/guide with the strength of a bear and the patience of a teacher. 

#coynesurvivalschools #survival #wildernesssurvival #outdoorsman #outdoors #camping #winter #adventure #reels #igers #igdaily 

And to my friends Taylor, Nakisa, Aaron, Ben, Mica, Jeremy, Simon, Christina, and Chia, it was great training with you. Cheers to future adventures. 🍻

If you want to be strong, learn to enjoy being alone. -Anne Frank

I have found that the most powerful humans I’ve come in contact with have faced challenges alone. 

Those with the ability to face the world alone are titans among men and women, for you must have near total control of your mind to stay in a relaxed and peaceful state. Fear must be replaced with confidence. Anxiety must be replaced with resolve. Loneliness must be replaced with contentment. 

We enter this world alone, and we will leave alone. As an individual you are powerful alone. Always remember this. Start training yourself through meditation and fitness. Those things do not need to wait until you’re in a group setting or at the gym. Do it alone. Do it lonely. Do it scared. Make yourself comfortable with alone, and one day you will be unbreakable.

While looking through old photos and videos to find something to post for @tristinmays birthday…I was pretty shocked to see my own personal transformation over the past few years. 
\\\
I was comfortable…complacent…conceited…floating through life; following my wife…following others…wasting time…waiting for things to fall into my lap. 
The pandemic was a brick wall in my life. All of a sudden, nothing in my life was working the way it was supposed to…and there was no guarantee things would ever work right again. 
But rather than let sadness, regret, anger, or anxiety take me down, I chose to act. 
I started spending more time alone. More time outdoors, more time exercising, exploring…reading…meditating…working towards a more peaceful, grounded, yet powerful version of myself. 
Then along came my son. 
After that first look into his eyes 10/3/21, the fire in my soul was stoked along with a message to become a stronger man and leader by any means necessary…
To fear nothing but God. I have heeded that message, and I’ll continue to do so until my last day.  For myself, for my tribe, for you, and all others who entrust me with their support.

This is the way. 🙏❤️‍🔥

I used to fly kites as a teenager. Is that cool or lame?

It certainly didn’t SOUND like a cool hobby to other people in my community at the time, so I really never talked about it with friends. 
Regardless, my dad and I would hop in the truck and drive to the park and just fly kites sometimes.
There was something so liberating about it. 
It was usually cold and windy, so it felt mentally and physically demanding. Felt good.

You had to use all the muscles in your arms and hands to “feel” the wind from the ground. Complete focus.
It’s like dancing in the sky; the kite, an extension of yourself. 
Or like painting on an infinite canvas. 

I haven’t flown a kite in a decade, but finding this video just now was nice.

Different forms of outdoor activity have always kept me grounded. Even something as simple as flying a kite and drawing on the sky.

Victoria Mays

You’ll know when it’s time. 💎😏

Really though. I feel there is a window of time a man should propose. That window is between 1-3 years of a relationship with a woman. You’ll know when the time is right. You should feel that she would say yes, without explicitly talking about it. If she talks about your future together, kids, etc. you’ll know it’s about that time. Dragging a relationship out with a young woman beyond 3 years without considering marriage is inappropriate. But don’t let a woman make your decisions for you when it comes to the details around your proposal or the ring. Do it yourself. Do the best you can do. The most ring you can afford within reason. You propose when you are ready. Trust me she will respect you more in the long run, knowing it was ALL you, regardless if it’s what she “wanted.” 💪

Walking outdoors is not only good for your physical health, it’s great for your mental health. We spend most of our time toiling away at work or hobbies. So much so, we forget to just exist.

Hiking, to me, is a form of meditation. Clearing away distracting thoughts to make room for focus on the trail ahead. I always feel better after a hike, no matter how good or crappy things might be at the time. Do you ever go on hikes? If so, tag your hiking partners. You guys are killin it and you probably have frequently refreshed patience and energy to show for it. 🤙

Neither masculinity nor femininity is inherently toxic. Only our view of them, which subsequently affects our interactions. Masculinity and femininity are both divine. Period. Pop culture will have you believe ~ men and women are in competition with one another. We can’t trust each other. The other is always out to take advantage in some way. One is inferior. ~ This has spawned several generations of discord between the genders. Outliers exist, sure. But as a whole, we are literally made for each other and we should all start acting like it. ❤️ Do you agree?

Mom tells me that when I was 2-3 years old, I used to sneak out of my room in the middle of the night, walk into the living room, hop on the couch, turn on the tv, and find golf. I’d sit there alone in the dark watching for hours until they realized where I was.

But growing up in New York, little boys played baseball, so that’s what I played for about 10 years. Good baseball too. I was a pitcher for the most part, but also played shortstop, third base, and center field throughout my little league days. 

I would still catch glimpses of golf on tv now and then, and wished I knew how to play. Well, when I was 16 years old, my family moved to Southern California and I got my wish. 

We moved into a house that was walking distance from a golf course, and my mom got me and my sister @tristinmays lessons. We had this legendary coach I’ll never forget. I remember feeling the air shake when he’d make contact with the ball. Every single shot. I just wanted to be as powerful as him someday. 

I can’t remember his name for anything, but he’s a figure in my memory that is larger than life, like a god. A tall, surly, confident man with dirty blonde hair and old clubs. He always treated me with great respect, and felt it was his duty to ensure I became a great player since I was probably the only child of color that had stepped foot on that golf course. 

He had his work cut out for him though, as I had developed a decade of baseball habits that had to be broken or tweaked. My driver was my weak point largely because of my baseball swing. 

I specifically remember one morning we were on a mountain course, the rain was coming down, we were the only ones out there. He was giving me direction from the safety of his golf cart while I was standing out at the tee in the rain. I had a fear of hitting homes that were on either side of the fairway (it’s very easy to hit a bad drive and end up in someone’s window or backyard.) So I choked back. Didn’t swing hard.

I’ll always remember him shouting out something to the effect of “just swing the darn club, Jeryn, they all have insurance.” And I broke my fear of swinging hard off the tee that day. 

#golf #golfstories #story #lessons
